               <p rend="typology" xml:space="preserve">West (Maghreb) › Tunisia › Central Tunisia  </p>
               <p>Bedouin-type dialect</p>
            </div>
            <div type="general">
               <p xml:space="preserve">Douara is a village situated in the rural surroundings of the town of Mezzouna in the Central Tunisian Sidi Bouzid Governorate. Located in the Central Tunisian steppe, it is a mainly agricultural area. As for the town of Mezzouna, it is a crossing point of the highways connecting the governorate of Sidi Bouzid with the Gafsa and Sfax Governorates. </p>
               <p xml:space="preserve">The predominant tribal group in Douara are the Ouled Amour (Ūlǟd ʕMuṛ), which at the same time is the alternative name of this village. The Ouled Amour are divided into the tribal groups of the Ouled Aay (Ūlǟd il-ʕĀy), Ouled Massoud (Ūlǟd Masʕūd), the Hdhab (l-ᵃHḏāb) and the Shwashniya (iš-Šwǟšnīya). </p>
               <p xml:space="preserve">Concerning folk religion, the local saint of Douara is Sidi Bou Kthir (Sīdi Bū Kṯīr).</p>
            </div>
            <div type="researchHistory">
               <p xml:space="preserve">To the best of our knowledge hitherto no research has been done on the dialect of Douara, however this dialect is linguistically investigated within the TUNOCENT project.</p>
            </div>
